{{Infobox Treaty |name = Hague Marriage Convention |long_name = Convention of 14 March 1978 on Celebration and Recognition of the Validity of Marriages |image = |caption = |type = |date_drafted = |date_signed = 25 March 1978 |location_signed = The Netherlands |date_sealed = |date_effective = 1 May 1991 |condition_effective = ratification by 3 states |date_expiration = |signatories = 6 |parties = 3 (Australia, Luxembourg, Netherlands) |depositor = [[Ministry of Foreign Affairs (Netherlands)]] |language = |languages = French and English |wikisource = }}
The '''Hague Convention on Celebration and Recognition of the Validity of Marriages''' or '''Hague Marriage Convention''' is a [[multilateralism|multilateral]] [[treaty]] developed by the [[Hague Conference on Private International Law]] that provides the recognition of marriages. The convention was signed in 1978 by Portugal, Luxembourg and Egypt, and later by Australia, Finland and the Netherlands. It entered into force more than 10 years after opening for signature after ratification by Australia, the Netherlands (for its European territory only)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.minbuza.nl/nl/Producten_en_Diensten/Overige_diensten/Verdragen/Zoek_in_de_Verdragenbank?isn=000878|language=Dutch|title=Detailpagina Verdragenbank, Verdrag inzake de voltrekking en de erkenning van de geldigheid van huwelijken|publisher=[[Cabinet of the Netherlands|Government of the Netherlands]]|accessdate=6 March 2011}}</ref> and Luxembourg, and no countries have acceded to the convention since.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hcch.net/index_en.php?act=conventions.text&cid=88|title=Status table|publisher=[[Hague Conference on Private International Law]]|accessdate=6 March 2011}}</ref>
